Q17. How would you implement a fixed-size connection pool?
Easy answer: Use a BlockingQueue to hold available connections. acquire() polls/takes with timeout, release() validates and returns to the queue, close() drains resources. Make it thread-safe, avoid returning broken connections, and expose metrics for active/idle/wait count.
Simple example: Keep five connections in an ArrayBlockingQueue. A caller takes one, uses it, and returns it in a finally block.
Code / command example
public final class SimpleConnectionPool implements AutoCloseable {
    private final BlockingQueue<Connection> available;

    public SimpleConnectionPool(List<Connection> connections) {
        this.available = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(connections.size());
        this.available.addAll(connections);
    }

    public Connection acquire(long timeout, TimeUnit unit)
            throws InterruptedException, TimeoutException {
        Connection connection = available.poll(timeout, unit);
        if (connection == null) throw new TimeoutException("No connection available");
        return connection;
    }

    public void release(Connection connection) {
        if (connection != null) available.offer(connection);
    }

    @Override public void close() throws SQLException {
        Connection c;
        while ((c = available.poll()) != null) c.close();
    }
}
